## Notable people

Cremona has been the birthplace or adopted home of a remarkable array of individuals:

*   [Publius Quinctilius Varus](/Publius_Quinctilius_Varus) (46 BC – AD 9), a Roman general and politician whose career took a disastrous turn in Germania.
*   [Marcus Furius Bibaculus](/Marcus_Furius_Bibaculus) (c. 103 BC – ? BC), a Roman poet known for his satirical verse, though much of his work is now lost.
*   [Liutprand of Cremona](/Liutprand_of_Cremona) (c. 920 – 972), a bishop of Cremona, historian, and diplomat whose writings offer valuable insights into 10th-century European politics.
*   [Saint Homobonus](/Saint_Homobonus) (12th century), the revered patron saint of Cremona, also recognized as the patron of business people, tailors, shoemakers, and clothworkers.
*   [Gerard of Cremona](/Gerard_of_Cremona) (c. 1114 – 1187), a pivotal figure in the history of science, renowned for his translation of crucial scientific texts from Arabic into Latin, significantly enriching Western knowledge.
*   [Sicard of Cremona](/Sicard_of_Cremona) (1155–1215), a prominent prelate, historian, and writer of his time.
*   [Bernardino Ricca](/Bernardino_Ricca) (1450–?), a painter whose contributions to the art of the period are documented.
*   [Filippo de Lurano](/Filippo_de_Lurano) (c. 1475 – after 1520), an Italian composer of the Renaissance whose musical works have been preserved.
*   [Marco Girolamo Vida](/Marco_Girolamo_Vida) (c. 1489 – 1566), a distinguished scholar, celebrated Latin poet, and bishop, known for his erudition.
*   [Altobello Melone](/Altobello_Melone) (c. 1490 – before 1543), an Italian painter of the Renaissance whose artistic style is recognized.
*   [Francesco and Giuseppe Dattaro](/Dattaro_family) (c. 1495 – 1576 & c. 1540 – 1616), a father and son duo of architects who left their mark on the city's built environment.
